\par The first time the program is started it will create a wsendmail.ini file in your Windows directory. This file must be edited so that the program knows the address (domain {\b name} - not IP number) of your SMTP se
rver, the default return path and the nicknames of all receivers of email when it is used as a CGI-BIN app.
\par 
\par Below is the syntax if you use the program from the DOS command line:
\par 
\par \pard \fi720\nowidctlpar wSendmail [-debug] [-verbose] [-mime] [-sSubject] [-fFrom] \{to[,to] | @addr_list_file\} mail_file
\par wSendmail [-debug] [-verbose] [-mime] [-sSubject] [-fFrom] \{to[,to] | @addr_list_file\} < message
\par \pard \nowidctlpar Example:
\par \tab wSendmail -v "-sTest message" -fme@somewhere.com someone@somewhere.com
\par \tab (Since no mail_file is given, you must type in the message body from the keyboard)
\par 
\par Line parameters are not used when running as CGI-BIN app.
\par 
\par The parameters in is square brackets are optional.
\par 
\par \tab {\b -debug} enables logging of the mail transaction. 
\par \tab {\b -verbose} enables logging of the result of the transaction
\par \tab {\b -s} specifies the subject of the message. 
\par \tab {\b -f} identifies the sender of the mail.
\par \tab -{\b mime} disables mime encoding
\par 
\par If you use the program as a CGI-BIN app, copy it to your CGI-BIN directory and call it from your HTML Forms. A sample page is included with this distribution.
\par 
\par  If used as a CGI-BIN app, the following fields are required:
\par 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20\lang1033 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-283\li991\nowidctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent283 {\pntxtb \'b7}}"from" = senders email address (will map to "someone@somewhere.com" if not filled in
\par \pard \fi-283\li991\nowidctlpar \tab 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20\lang1033 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-283\li991\nowidctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent283 {\pntxtb \'b7}}
"RCPT" = Receiver of the email. There can me any number of receivers. This field will typically be hidden. The data value of this filed is a nickname defined in the wsendmail.ini file in your windows directory. This way mail can only be sent {\b\i to}
 mailboxes authorized by you. 
\par \pard \fi-283\li991\nowidctlpar \tab 
\par {\pntext\pard\plain\f1\fs20\lang1033 \'b7\tab}\pard \fi-283\li991\nowidctlpar{\*\pn \pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent283 {\pntxtb \'b7}}"subject" = The subject field in the email. Typically used to  identify the page HTTP that generated the email.
\par \pard \nowidctlpar 
\par Any other form fields will be included in the message body with the filed name as a header, and the contents following on the next line. This version supports a total of  500 fields.
\par 
\par {\i Note that the filed labels are case sensitive.
\par }
\par The program supports mime 1.0 encoding of European national characters.
\par It also applies to the RFC 821 and RFC 822 specs.33999
\par In CGI-BIN mode the program supports any number of recipients. In command line mode you can specify multiple recipients by separating them with comma (jgaa@online.no,whoever@somewhere.com) or by replacing the to parameter with a "@filename". The @ tells 
wSendmail that the recipients are in the filename. The recipients file is a standard ASCII file with one email address on each line.
\par 
\par The program will automatically detect if it is started by a HTTP server as a CGI-BIN app, and output a confirmation page in standard HTML 1 format. The HTML code is defined in the "wSendmail.ini" file, and can be modified to suit your needs.
\par 
\par \pard \widctlpar 
\par {\b wSendmail.ini}
\par 
\par The wSendmail.ini file is located in your Windows directory. It is created and configures with default values the first time the program is started. You must configure this file before wSendmail will work.
\par 
\par The following is a description of the fields in the .ini file:
\par 
\par \pard \li720\widctlpar {\f11\fs16 [wSendmail]
\par 
\par ; The SMTP host where wSendmail will post emails
\par ; This field *must* be configured with your SMTP host
\par SMTP Host=mail.online.no
\par 
\par ; The default return path
\par ; Put your email POP3 account here
\par Return Path=jgaa@online.no
\par 
\par ; Shall wSendmail delete the message body file?
\par ; Applies only when running in command line mode
\par Delete File When Used=No
\par 
\par ; The HTML code used in the header. Must be less than 127 characters.
\par HTML Head=<html><body><H1>Mail Confirmation</H1><hr><p>
\par HTML OK=<h4>Message sent.</h4></body></html>
\par HTML Fail=<H3>Error %d %s.<br> Message could not be forwarded</h3></body></html>
\par 
\par ; Allow real email addresses to be used in forms?
\par ; If not, the forms must use a nickname from the [Nicknames] section below
\par Restrict Email=No
\par 
\par ; Use Microsoft Internet Information Server HTTP header?
\par ; If your server complains about the header, change this to Yes or No.
\par IIS header=Yes
\par 
\par ; Enable MIME character encoding?
\par Mime Encoding=Yes
\par 
\par ; Valid nicknames. The nickname is used in the HTML form and referrers to a
\par ; email address. 
\par [Nicknames]
\par 
\par jgaa=jgaa@jgaa.ldp.no
\par jgaa-at-telepost=jgaa@telepost.no
\par jgaa-test=jgaatest@ldp.no
\par jgaatest=jgaatest@ldp.no
\par }\pard \widctlpar 
\par {\b Trouble shooting.}
\par 
\par If you have trouble getting the program to work, run it from the command line with the -debug flag. This will allow you to monitor the communication between the SMTP server and wSendmail.
\par 
\par \tab {\f11 wSendmail -debug -ttest Your.Email}{\f11\fs16 @wherever.com}{\f11 
